---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import ReplyTask from '../../../../../components/ReplyTask.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const requestCode = `public record AddCartItemRequest(
    string Sku,
    int Quantity);`;

const endpointCode = `app.MapPost("/cart/items", (AddCartItemRequest request) =>
{
    if (request.Quantity <= 0)
    {
        return Results.BadRequest(new
        {
            error = "Quantity must be greater than zero."
        });
    }

    return Results.Ok(new
    {
        accepted = true,
        sku = request.Sku,
        quantity = request.Quantity
    });
});`;

const positiveBody = `{
  "sku": "ABC-123",
  "quantity": 2
}`;

const zeroBody = `{
  "sku": "ABC-123",
  "quantity": 0
}`;

const replyText = `[learn:dotnet/008:q1]

Read the supplied code only. Do not write or run a project.

Request type:
public record AddCartItemRequest(
    string Sku,
    int Quantity);

Handler:
app.MapPost("/cart/items", (AddCartItemRequest request) =>
{
    if (request.Quantity <= 0)
    {
        return Results.BadRequest(new { error = "Quantity must be greater than zero." });
    }

    return Results.Ok(new
    {
        accepted = true,
        sku = request.Sku,
        quantity = request.Quantity
    });
});

Request 1:
{"sku":"ABC-123","quantity":2}

Request 2:
{"sku":"ABC-123","quantity":0}

A. Does the type int itself reject 0? Which expression enforces the positive-quantity rule?
Answer:

B. For Request 1, is request.Quantity <= 0 true or false? Give the exact HTTP status and returned JSON values.
Answer:

C. For Request 2, is request.Quantity <= 0 true or false? Give the exact HTTP status and returned JSON values.
Answer:

Exact JSON spacing and property order do not matter. Property names and values do matter.`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 8 · .NET: positive quantity rule"
  heading="Trace one positive-quantity runtime rule"
  lede="Read a supplied request type and handler. Decide what int permits, test one condition with two values, and predict each response."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="Type and rule are different">
    <Callout>
      <code>int</code> represents whole numbers. It permits negative numbers, <code>0</code>, and positive numbers. It does not mean “positive number.”
    </Callout>
    <p>This endpoint needs a separate runtime rule. The condition <code>request.Quantity &lt;= 0</code> rejects zero and negative quantities.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Supplied request type">
    <Code code={requestCode} lang="csharp" />
    <p>The request has a product code and a whole-number quantity. The record carries the values. The handler applies the positive-quantity rule.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Supplied handler">
    <Code code={endpointCode} lang="csharp" />
    <ul>
      <li>If <code>request.Quantity &lt;= 0</code> is <code>true</code>, the handler returns <code>400 Bad Request</code>.</li>
      <li>If it is <code>false</code>, execution continues to <code>200 OK</code>.</li>
    </ul>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Two complete request bodies">
    <p><strong>Request 1: quantity 2</strong></p>
    <Code code={positiveBody} lang="json" />
    <p><strong>Request 2: quantity 0</strong></p>
    <Code code={zeroBody} lang="json" />
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:dotnet/008:q1" copyText={replyText} difficulty={3}>
    <p>Answer three short questions. Read the code only; do not create or run a project.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Does <code>int</code> itself reject <code>0</code>? Which expression enforces the positive-quantity rule?</li>
      <li>For Request 1, is the condition <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>? Give the exact HTTP status and returned JSON values.</li>
      <li>For Request 2, is the condition <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>? Give the exact HTTP status and returned JSON values.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Exact JSON spacing and property order do not matter. Property names and values do matter.</p>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
